  "doc_id": "4521",
  "text": "Maize inbred resistance 1 (Mir1), a secreted maize PLCP that localized in vesicle, showed high accumulation at the wounding site after larval feeding . Tobacco budworm larvae feeding with Mir1-overexpressing plants caused severe damage to caterpillar for Mir1 degraded the peritrophic matrix of the insect gut [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Recent research showed that ethylene (ET) was required for accumulation of Mir1 and contributed to heighten resistance to corn leaf aphid (CLA) in maize [CITATION_3] . In addition, PLCPs are also key regulators of salicylic acid (SA)-dependent defense signaling. Previous studies have shown that SA treatment can strongly induce PLCP protein activity in maize leaves, and the activated apoplastic PLCPs can in turn induce the expression of SArelated immune genes [CITATION_4] . The latest research reveals that PLCPs need to release Z. mays immune signaling peptide 1 (Zip1) through their protein precursors to induce SA accumulation and activate SA defense signaling in leaves [CITATION_5] . These results indicate that the interaction of SA with PLCPs plays a key role in the expression regulation of downstream defense genes under biotic stress.",
